# Pipelines Deep Dive

@meta {
  title: "Pipelines Deep Dive — The Operator That Changes Everything"
  date: "2024-11-15"
  author: "bad-antics"
  tags: ["pipelines", "operators", "functional", "internals"]
  reading_time: "12 min"
}

@heading level=1 {
  Pipelines Deep Dive
}

@subtitle {
  The |> operator that changes the way you think about data
}

---

@heading level=2 {
  A Brief History of Function Composition
}

@paragraph {
  Every programming language has a way to compose functions. In most languages,
  it's nested calls:
}

@code lang=python {
  # Python: inside-out, reads right-to-left
  result = sum(map(square, filter(is_even, numbers)))
}

@paragraph {
  In object-oriented languages, you chain methods:
}

@code lang=javascript {
  // JavaScript: reads left-to-right, but only for methods
  const result = numbers.filter(isEven).map(square).reduce((a,b) => a+b, 0)
}

@paragraph {
  Both approaches work. But both force you to think in a different direction
  than the data flows. And the OOP approach only works if the first value is
  an object with the right methods.
}

@paragraph {
  The pipeline operator solves this completely:
}

@code lang=lateralus {
  // LATERALUS: reads in the order operations happen
  let result = numbers
    |> filter(is_even)
    |> map(square)
    |> reduce((a, b) => a + b, 0)
}

---

@heading level=2 {
  How |> Works Under the Hood
}

@paragraph {
  The pipeline operator @code{|>} is a binary infix operator that desugars
  during compilation. At the AST level, @code{x |> f(y)} becomes @code{f(x, y)}.
}

@paragraph {
  More precisely: the value on the left is inserted as the *first argument*
  of the function call on the right. If the right side is a bare identifier
  (not a call), it's treated as @code{f(x)}.
}

@code lang=lateralus {
  // These are identical:
  "hello" |> upper()
  upper("hello")

  // These are also identical:
  list |> filter(is_even)
  filter(list, is_even)

  // Multi-argument functions work naturally:
  data |> group_by((x) => x.category)
  group_by(data, (x) => x.category)
}

@paragraph {
  The compiler transforms the AST before IR generation — pipelines have
  zero runtime overhead compared to direct function calls.
}

---

@heading level=2 {
  The Optional Pipeline: |?
}

@paragraph {
  Real programs deal with missing data. The @code{|?} operator is a
  "null-propagating" pipeline: if the left side is @code{None}, the entire
  pipeline short-circuits and returns @code{None} without calling the function.
}

@code lang=lateralus {
  // Without |?, you'd write:
  let result = if user != None {
    let trimmed = trim(user.input)
    if trimmed != None {
      let parsed = parse_int(trimmed)
      if parsed != None { validate_range(parsed, 0, 100) } else { None }
    } else { None }
  } else { None }

  // With |?, it's one expression:
  let result = user
    |? .input
    |? trim()
    |? parse_int()
    |? validate_range(0, 100)
}

@paragraph {
  This is equivalent to Haskell's @code{Maybe} monad bind operation, or
  Kotlin's safe-call operator @code{?.}, extended to arbitrary function calls.
}

---

@heading level=2 {
  Pipelines as First-Class Values
}

@paragraph {
  In LATERALUS, pipeline *chains* can be stored and reused:
}

@code lang=lateralus {
  // A pipeline stage is just a function
  let normalize = (text: str) => text
    |> trim()
    |> lower()
    |> replace("[^a-z0-9 ]", "")
    |> split(" ")
    |> filter((w) => len(w) > 2)

  // Reuse it anywhere
  let words_a = normalize(document_a)
  let words_b = normalize(document_b)
  let similarity = jaccard_similarity(words_a, words_b)
}

@paragraph {
  This composability is what makes LATERALUS programs naturally modular.
  Each pipeline stage is a pure function. Pure functions are easy to test,
  easy to reason about, and easy to combine.
}

---

@heading level=2 {
  The Optimizer's Role
}

@paragraph {
  The LATERALUS optimizer (at O2 and above) analyzes pipeline chains and
  can apply *pipeline fusion*: combining multiple map/filter operations into
  a single pass over the data.
}

@code lang=lateralus {
  // At O2, this:
  data
    |> filter(pred_a)
    |> map(transform_a)
    |> filter(pred_b)
    |> map(transform_b)

  // Becomes roughly equivalent to:
  data |> map_filter_chain([pred_a, transform_a, pred_b, transform_b])
}

@paragraph {
  This matters for large datasets. Instead of four passes over potentially
  millions of elements, you get one. The optimizer detects these fusion
  opportunities automatically.
}

---

@heading level=2 {
  Pipeline-Oriented Design Patterns
}

@heading level=3 {
  Pattern 1: The ETL Pipeline
}

@code lang=lateralus {
  fn process_sensor_data(raw: list) {
    raw
      |> validate_readings()            // E: extract valid readings
      |> normalize_units("SI")          // T: transform to SI units
      |> apply_calibration(sensor_id)   // T: hardware calibration
      |> remove_outliers(sigma=3.0)     // T: statistical cleaning
      |> smooth(window=10)              // T: sliding window average
      |> store_to_db("sensor_archive")  // L: load to storage
  }
}

@heading level=3 {
  Pattern 2: The Validation Chain
}

@code lang=lateralus {
  fn validate_user_input(raw: str) -> Result {
    raw
      |? trim()
      |? validate_not_empty("username cannot be empty")
      |? validate_length(3, 32, "username must be 3-32 chars")
      |? validate_regex("[a-z0-9_]+", "alphanumeric and underscore only")
      |? check_not_taken(user_db)
  }
}

@heading level=3 {
  Pattern 3: The Analysis Pipeline
}

@code lang=lateralus {
  fn analyze_genome(sequence: str) {
    sequence
      |> parse_fasta()
      |> quality_filter(min_score=30)
      |> align_to_reference(genome_ref)
      |> call_variants(confidence=0.95)
      |> annotate_variants(db=clinvar)
      |> generate_report(format="html")
  }
}

---

@heading level=2 {
  Parallel Pipelines (v1.4 Preview)
}

@paragraph {
  Coming in v1.4: the @code{|>>} parallel pipeline operator splits the
  collection across CPU cores automatically:
}

@code lang=lateralus {
  // |>> uses parallel map internally
  large_dataset
    |>> expensive_transform()    // runs on all cores
    |>> validate_result()        // parallel validation
    |>  collect()                // merge back to single thread
}

---

@heading level=2 {
  Summary
}

@paragraph {
  The pipeline operator is the most fundamental abstraction in LATERALUS.
  It's not a feature. It's the philosophy of the language made concrete:
  data flows through transformations naturally, readably, and efficiently.
}

@paragraph {
  Every time you write @code{|>}, you're writing code that reads exactly
  like the problem it solves. And that's what programming should always feel like.
}

